{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641015"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:21:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:21:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17854"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17854"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10568"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97376"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10058"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24643"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlycogen synthesis is tightly regulated in human cells to maintain glucose homeostasis. Several metabolites can influence the activity of the enzymes involved in this process.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the allosteric activator of glycogen synthase?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glucose-6-phosphate","Fructose-1,6-bisphosphate","Adenosine triphosphate","Pyruvate","Lactate"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary allosteric activator of glycogen synthase. When cellular glucose levels rise, increased G6P concentrations activate glycogen synthase through binding to an allosteric site. This causes a conformational change that increases the enzyme\u0027s activity, promoting glycogen storage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe allosteric regulation by G6P provides rapid metabolic control that operates alongside slower hormonal regulation via insulin. This dual control ensures efficient glycogen synthesis when glucose is abundant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFructose-1,6-bisphosphate\u003C/strong\u003E is a glycolytic intermediate that primarily signals high glucose flux through glycolysis. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdenosine triphosphate\u003C/strong\u003E serves as the glucose-phosphorylating agent in glycogen synthesis but does not allosterically regulate glycogen synthase. \u003Cstrong\u003EPyruvate\u003C/strong\u003E signals the end product of glycolysis and is a substrate for gluconeogenesis but does not regulate glycogen synthesis. \u003Cstrong\u003ELactate\u003C/strong\u003E is converted to glucose via gluconeogenesis during exercise but has no direct effect on glycogen synthase activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis feed-forward activation by G6P ensures that glycogen synthesis increases when glucose is abundant, helping to prevent hyperglycaemia and store energy for future use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Glucose-6-phosphate (G6P) is an allosteric activator of glycogen synthase, promoting glycogen synthesis when glucose levels are high.","Glycogen synthase catalyses the addition of glucose units to form glycogen chains via \u03b1-1,4 glycosidic bonds.","Allosteric regulation by G6P provides rapid control of glycogen synthesis independent of hormonal signals."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97376"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17854"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97376"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T13:00:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T13:00:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10568"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115373"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description"